"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78408","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-08-07","<p> </p><p>The Sentinel aircraft fleet is supported by a number of logistic support contracts, each of which has a different expiry date. Defence Equipment and Support is currently working to extend all contracts before their respective expiry dates.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-08-07T10:56:30.7492995Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78408/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78408/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the new contract to extend the life of the Sentinel aircraft until 2018 will be signed.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","206329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78409","Cabinet Office","false","2014-09-01","<p>Sir John Holmes’ further work to implement the recommendations set out in his Military Medals Review included a review of the case for some form of National Defence Medal, to recognise all military service. As Sir John noted in his report of July 2012, the National Defence Medal is an issue of national significance which would require a broad political and public consensus and consideration by the government as a whole, in consultation with other political parties and concerned organisations.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-09-01T11:17:55.6617761Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78409/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78409/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-16","Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to make an announcement on recommendations relating to the award of the National Defence Medal.","false","Biography information for Sir Bob Russell","Colchester","Sir Bob Russell","206314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78410","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence procures naval vessels in accordance with EU procurement regulations. The procurement of complex warships and submarines is covered by an exemption to these regulations, Article 346 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union, which allows any EU member state to take measures to protect its essential security interests. We will give full regard to our national security interests beyond 2014, using exemptions under Article 346 as appropriate.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-21T15:49:59.9752558Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78410/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78410/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Warships: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his policy is on where naval vessels should be constructed after 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","206162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78411","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>There are presently over 3,000 cadets in Northern Ireland of which over 2,000 are Army Cadets. These cadets are drawn from across a wide spectrum of the community.<br><br>The Reserve Forces and Cadets Association of Northern Ireland are planning to launch a new recruitment campaign in August working in partnership with a number of external agencies.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-07-22T17:00:01.3638755Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78411/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78411/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78411/answer/previousversion/11788","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Army: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has to promote recruitment to the army cadets in Northern Ireland in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","206163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78412","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-30","<p> </p><p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-30T11:46:58.5872845Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78412/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78412/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Defence Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions since 2010 product recall notices have been issued for equipment being used by the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","206183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78413","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>The total cost of a successful recruit at each establishment, based on their respective output, is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>ITC Catterick £33,706</p><p> </p><p>ATC Pirbright £20,253</p><p> </p><p>ATR Bassingbourn £24,187</p><p> </p><p>AFC Harrogate £68,751</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is based on full costs to the Army’s budget for 2013-14, and does not include infrastructure and equipment costs as these are managed collectively across a number of sites and equipment fleets and cannot be attributed to individual units. The cost for ATR Bassingbourn is based on costs for 2012/13 as this was the last year that Phase 1 training was carried out at that location.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All Junior Entry recruits undertake their initial training at AFC Harrogate. They are provided with highly valuable vocational training opportunities which result in some 85% leaving initial training with Level 2 qualifications in literacy and numeracy. The greater length of service of Junior Entry personnel results in the Army having to recruit and train fewer personnel. This training contributes not only to individual development, but to society in the long term.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-22T13:59:02.6437126Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78413/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78413/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78413/answer/previousversion/11787","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total cost was of each successfully trained recruit of (a) Phase 1 and 2 training at ITC Catterick, (b) Phase 1 training at ATC Pirbright, (c) Phase 1 training at ATR Bassingbourn and (d) Phase 1 training at AFC Harrogate including trainee salaries and associated costs in the most recent years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","206117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78414","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer My hon. Friend the Minister of State for Defence Personnel, Welfare and Veterans (Anna Soubry) gave to the hon. Member for Bridgend (Madeleine Moon) on 23 June 2014, (Official Report, column 88W). In addition, the annual salary for new entrants is £14,492 rising to £17,945 on completion of Phase 1 training in 2014-15. The number of trainees may vary each year.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","206119","2014-07-22T13:57:04.547282Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78414/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78414/answer","HOC 206118 Hansard Extract 23 June 2014.doc","HOC 206118 Hansard Extract 23 June 2014.doc","Hansard Extract 23 June 2014","Hansard Extract 23 June 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78414/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78414/answer/previousversion/11786","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total cost of running Phase 1 training at AFC Harrogate including trainee salaries and associated costs was in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","206118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78415","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer My hon. Friend the Minister of State for Defence Personnel, Welfare and Veterans (Anna Soubry) gave to the hon. Member for Bridgend (Madeleine Moon) on 23 June 2014, (Official Report, column 88W). In addition, the annual salary for new entrants is £14,492 rising to £17,945 on completion of Phase 1 training in 2014-15. The number of trainees may vary each year.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","206118","2014-07-22T13:57:04.7192014Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78415/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78415/answer","HOC 206118 Hansard Extract 23 June 2014.doc","HOC 206118 Hansard Extract 23 June 2014.doc","Hansard Extract 23 June 2014","Hansard Extract 23 June 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78415/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78415/answer/previousversion/11783","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Army: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total cost of running the Combat Infantryman's Course (Phase 1 and 2 training) at ITC Catterick including trainee salaries and associated costs was in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","206119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78416","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-08-04","<p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) estimates a cost of 18.9p for each Ministerial reply based on stationery costs. <br><br>In 2013, MOD Ministers responded to 4,853 letters from hon. Members and Peers, the cost of which would have been just under £920. <br><br>As replies to Parliamentarians are delivered by hand to Parliament, there is no cost incurred for postage.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-08-04T10:19:30.5683581Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78416/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78416/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will estimate the annual cost to his Department of (a) stationery and (b) postage incurred when sending a ministerial reply to hon. Members; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","206144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78417","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-01","<p>The cost to the public purse for attendance and related marketing material was around £5,500.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-01T13:03:21.51451Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78417/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78417/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) attendance by RAF Northolt personnel and (b) related marketing materials at the European Business Aviation Convention and Exhibition on 20 to 22 May 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Pound","Ealing North","Stephen Pound","206197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78418","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-01","<p>The fees charged at RAF Northolt are in excess of the amount required by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) to cover its costs in the provision of commercial services and are calculated to be at market rate. The MOD is therefore obtaining market value for the commercial services that it provides and so it does not constitute state aid.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-09-01T13:01:02.7585144Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78418/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78418/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-16","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what grounds he has concluded that the use of RAF Northolt for commercial flights does not constitute state aid; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Pound","Ealing North","Stephen Pound","206188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78419","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>In the June Statistical First Release we published data showing that there were 7,400 traineeships starts between August 2013 and April 2014 – the first nine months of the programme. We do not yet have reliable data to break this down further.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on traineeships data is published online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324016/traineeship-data-note-june14.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324016/traineeship-data-note-june14.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T16:31:24.2173549Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78419/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78419/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Training: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average duration is of all completed traineeships to date.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","206126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78420","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>In the June Statistical First Release we published data showing that there were 7,400 Traineeships starts between August 2013 and April 2014 – the first nine months of the programme. We do not yet have reliable data to break this down further.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further information on Traineeships data is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324016/traineeship-data-note-june14.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/324016/traineeship-data-note-june14.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-07-21T16:53:11.8647136Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78420/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78420/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78420/answer/previousversion/11717","Biography information for Matt Hancock","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-16","Training: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many traineeships completed to date have lasted six weeks or less.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","206127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78421","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>For the Education Funding Agency (EFA)-managed strand of the Youth Contract programme for 16- and 17-year-olds, payments are made on a ‘payment by results’ basis, which has three outcome-related payments.</p><p> </p><p>In announcing the programme, the Government committed £126 million over three years to provide capacity to support up to 55,000 young people who are aged 16 or 17, not in education, employment or training (NEET) and who have no GCSEs at grades A*-C. As a result of efficiency savings made during the procurement for delivery of the programme, in January 2013 the eligibility for the programme was extended to provide capacity for up to an additional 15,500 young people aged 16 or 17 who are NEET and: who have up to one GCSE A*-C or; who are care leavers/young people in care or; who are young offenders released from custody or serving community sentences.</p><p> </p><p>Delivery data for the programme for the period September 2012 to the end of March 2014 was published on 26 June 2014 and published online here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/youth-contract-delivery-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/youth-contract-delivery-data</a></p><p> </p><p>This shows contractors delivered 18,570 enrolments, 9,949 re-engagements and 3,445 sustained engagements. The contracted profile for the period 1 April 2014 to 31 March 2016 shows: 21,500 participant enrolments; 23,000 participant re-engagements into positive outcomes of education, training or employment with training; and 23,500 participants to sustain in a positive outcome of education, training or employment with training for five out of six months.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:41:25.2178032Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78421/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78421/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what target she has set for the number of 16 to 17 year olds to (a) enrol on the Youth Contract programme, (b) be re-engaged into a positive outcome following the Youth Contract programme and (c) be retained in that positive outcome for five out of six months over the course of the Youth Contract programme.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","206128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78422","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>Information is not available in the form requested. The report published by the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General (Official Report, 13 May 2014, 17WS) shows that Department for Education Ministers received 16,898 letters from parliamentarians in the 2013 calendar year. We do not keep records of the form in which replies to such letters are sent. As explained by the former Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Education and Childcare in the reply given to the hon. Member on 7 July, Official Report Column 151W, most correspondence from hon. Members continues to be received as letters and is replied to in the same format. Ministers do, however, reply by email when they consider it appropriate to do so.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T16:53:02.5971919Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78422/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78422/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate the annual cost to her Department of (a) stationery and (b) postage incurred when sending a ministerial reply to hon. Members; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","206145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78423","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Department of Education keeps the format of free school application forms under review. In doing so, the most important consideration is to ensure that applicants provide information in a way that allows officials to make the best possible judgement about the quality and suitability of the application.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:21:57.8391222Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78423/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78423/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 15 July 2014, Official Report, column 636W, on free schools, what assessment she has made of the feasibility of changes to the way personal information is recorded in free school applications to reduce the cost of redaction of that information; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","206239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78424","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The table below shows the amounts that have been paid since September 2012 by the Education Funding Agency (EFA) to the contractors delivering the EFA-managed element of the Youth Contract programme for 16- and 17-year-olds.</p><p> </p><p>This information relates only to the EFA-managed element of the Youth Contract for 16- and 17-year-olds. Funding for the Core Cities element of the programme, which is being delivered in Liverpool, Newcastle and Gateshead, and Leeds, Bradford and Wakefield, is devolved to the relevant local authorities.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Prime Contractor</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total amount paid since September 2012</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Skills Training UK Ltd</p></td><td><p>£2,060,685</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Prospects Services</p></td><td><p>£3,957,228</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Prevista Ltd</p></td><td><p>£298,344 (to 31 July 2013)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Consultancy Home Counties Ltd</p></td><td><p>£2,079,365</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Prospect Training Services (Gloucester) Ltd</p></td><td><p>£883,056</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pertemps People Development Group Ltd</p></td><td><p>£1,499,715</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Groundwork UK</p></td><td><p>£2,875,167</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:35:52.4729611Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78424/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78424/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much has been paid to each provider of the Youth Contract for 16 to 17 year olds since September 2012.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","206180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78425","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Trust reported to the Education Funding Agency (EFA) that a theft had occurred. The Trust undertook a full independent review, and the EFA monitored their response. The Department for Education’s most recent discussion with the Trust has been to confirm progress with the recovery of funds and the police investigation.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not had recent discussions with the Trust’s auditors. The EFA reviewed the most recent audited accounts in early 2014.</p><p>The Department does not hold a copy of the service level agreement between the Federation Trust and its schools.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","206165","2014-07-21T15:27:32.5339899Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78425/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78425/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Haberdashers' Aske's Federation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will place in the Library a copy of the service level agreement between the Haberdashers' Aske's Federation Trust and the schools in which it operates.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","206166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78426","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>There are currently 174 free schools open, with applications approved for a further 156 schools that are seeking to open in 2014/15 and beyond. Of these 330 schools, 4% do not currently have a permanent site identified. None of these schools are planning to open in September 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A full list of approved applications, showing the local authority, is published online:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/free-schools-successful-applications-and-open-schools-2014" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/free-schools-successful-applications-and-open-schools-2014</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:40:40.5345209Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78426/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78426/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools have been approved by her Department which do not have identified sites; and in which local authority area each such school wishes to operate.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","206167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78427","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>All disposals of publicly funded land by an academy would be judged on their individual merits and the Department for Education places no absolute thresholds in such cases. My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, would expect to balance the considerations listed against the circumstances under which the land in question is being disposed, and the future plans for it following disposal.</p><p>Guidance on academy land transfers is published online at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/254887/land_transfer_advice_april_2013.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/254887/land_transfer_advice_april_2013.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:33:49.8847636Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78427/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78427/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Academies: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 June 2014, Official Report, column 75W, on academies: land, what (a) amount of public investment and degree of enhancement, (b) amount of private investment and degree of enhancement, (c) length of time the land has been in public use and (d) value of land at the date of determination would trigger a determination in order to protect the public investment in land where it ceases to be used by an academy.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","206202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78428","Department for Education","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Only young people who meet the eligibility criteria set out in the Traineeships Framework for Delivery can take up a traineeship. For 2013/14, the core target group for traineeships are young people aged 16-23 who:</p><p>1. are not currently in a job and have little work experience, but who are focused on work or the prospect of it;</p><p>2. are 16-19 and qualified below Level 3 or 19-23 and have not yet achieved a full Level 2; and whom</p><p>3. providers and employers believe have a reasonable chance of being ready for employment or an apprenticeship within six months of engaging in a traineeship.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education does not collect information centrally on traineeship applications in the same way that the Department does not collect data on applications for other pre-employment training provision.</p><p> </p><p>In June we published data showing that there were 7,400 traineeships starting between August 2013 and April 2014 – the first nine months of the programme. We do not yet have reliable data to break this down by age-range and we do not collect information on the number of unsuccessful applications.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on traineeships data is published online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-other-statistics-and-research" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-other-statistics-and-research</a></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-07-22T09:21:51.1673347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78428/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78428/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78428/answer/previousversion/11327","Biography information for Nick Boles","60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Training: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of the core target group of 16 to 19 year olds have (a) applied for and (b) been accepted onto a traineeship to date.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","206213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78429","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>In 2012/13, 28% (481,600) of 16- to 18-year-olds had not achieved Level 2 English by the end of the previous academic year, and of those 53% (254,100) were not continuing to study the subject at any level.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012/13, 30% (518,300) of 16- to 18-year-olds had not achieved Level 2 mathematics by the end of the previous academic year, and of those 57% (295,500) were not continuing to study the subject at any level.</p><p> </p><p>This is why this Government has introduced a condition of funding to ensure that all 16- to 19-year-olds who have not secured a good GCSE pass in English or maths have the opportunity to achieve these subjects by 19.</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 is the latest year that we have participation data linked to prior attainment.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:51:12.4224754Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78429/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78429/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many 16 to 19 year olds who have not achieved English and mathematics to level two are not continuing to study these subjects.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","206214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78430","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>At the end of 2013, 1,094,000 young people aged 16-18 were studying on full-time study programmes in state-funded post-16 institutions (excluding higher education and independent schools). Of the remainder, 494,000 were in full-time education in independent schools, higher education, or part-time education; 220,000 were in other training or employment; and 148,000 were not in education, training or employment (NEET).</p><p> </p><p>It is up to schools, colleges and training providers to tailor study programmes to meet the career aspirations of students based on their prior attainment. The principal components of a 16-19 study programme include typically a substantial qualification (such as one or more A levels or Tech Levels), work experience and other non-qualification activity. English and maths also feature for students who failed to achieve an A*-C GCSE in maths and English by age 16.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:48:10.7581384Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78430/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78430/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many 16 to 19 year olds are not undertaking a study programme.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","206215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78431","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>There are currently 34 academy brokers. The Department for Education spent £3,031,794.39 on academy brokers in 2013-14.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T16:36:55.4543773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78431/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78431/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many academy brokers there are; and how much her Department has spent on academy brokers in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","206216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78432","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>Legal costs on appealing decision notices served by the Information Commissioner are not held centrally by the Department for Education, and the cost of determining these over the past five years would exceed the disproportionate limit.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T16:31:28.4147466Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78432/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78432/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on legal costs on appealing decision notices served by the Information Commissioner since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","206217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78433","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Trust reported to the Education Funding Agency (EFA) that a theft had occurred. The Trust undertook a full independent review, and the EFA monitored their response. The Department for Education’s most recent discussion with the Trust has been to confirm progress with the recovery of funds and the police investigation.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not had recent discussions with the Trust’s auditors. The EFA reviewed the most recent audited accounts in early 2014.</p><p>The Department does not hold a copy of the service level agreement between the Federation Trust and its schools.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","206166","2014-07-21T15:27:32.0027086Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78433/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78433/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Haberdashers' Aske's Federation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions her Department has had with (a) the Haberdashers' Aske's Federation Trust and (b) that Trust's auditors on possible fraud within the Trust.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","206165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78434","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>As companies and charitable trusts, academy trusts are required to appoint independent auditors to report on their financial statements. It is for the academy trust to manage the contract for their services.</p><p> </p><p>Auditors are qualified accountants and regulated by their professional institutes. The institutes undertake a programme of quality assurance visits to ensure firms are operating in accordance with expected professional standards. The outcomes of these reviews are publically available.</p><p> </p><p>The Education Funding Agency (EFA) supplements the various institute regulatory regimes with:</p><p> </p><p>· reviews of academy trusts’ audited financial statements, the associated audit reports on these and auditor management letters. The EFA follows up significant issues with individual trusts and their auditors;</p><p>· regular attendance at sector training events and delivery of online presentations/webinars for auditors on the key issues arising from reviews, to help ensure they are aware of the requirements expected of them and key risk areas; and</p><p>· responding to auditor queries received through the academy questions mailbox. <br><br></p><p>Other professional services provided to academy trusts will also be regulated by their relevant institute body, e.g. the Law Society.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T15:25:33.334234Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78434/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78434/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what checks the Education Funding Agency makes on the quality of auditors and others taking professional fees for services provided to academies.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","206234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78435","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The full list of Ministerial responsibilities will be published on <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a> in due course.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-21T16:36:45.3410423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78435/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78435/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the responsibilities will be of the Minister of State in her Department, the hon. Member for Bognor Regis and Littlehampton.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","206249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78436","Department for Education","false","2014-07-22","<p>This question is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the hon. Member. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House Library.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-22T15:44:52.3302566Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78436/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78436/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Schools: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Ofsted inspections were carried out in the local education authority of Birmingham in (a) primary, (b) secondary, (c) straight-through, (d) nursery and (e) other schools in the academic years (i) 2011-12, (ii) 2012-13 and (iii) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","206315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78437","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>No guidance has been provided to Ofsted inspectors by the Department for Education about the monitoring of school engagement with Prevent as the training of inspectors is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector.</p><p> </p><p>Where relevant, Ofsted provides inspectors with appropriate briefing on the Prevent agenda and gives training to inspectors ahead of inspection.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-21T13:47:29.9816769Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78437/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78437/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Schools: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance (a) her Department and (b) Ofsted provides to Ofsted inspectors about the monitoring of school engagement with Prevent.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","206357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78438","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-02","<p>The Government announced an increase of 3.34% to maximum maintenance loans for the 2015/16 academic year earlier this year. This increase will apply to all rates of maintenance loan, including the higher rate loan for students living away from home and studying in London, where living costs (including those for accommodation) are generally higher.</p><p>Decisions on student support arrangements for higher education courses are taken on an annual basis. The Government will review student support arrangements for the 2016/17 academic year in 2015.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-09-02T12:45:23.1847614Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78438/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78438/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-16","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if she will take steps to increase maintenance loans for university accommodation in respect of (a) students in places with expensive accommodation costs and (b) other students.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","206377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78439","Department for Education","false","2014-07-21","<p>The information requested is not available for teachers in specific grades.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-21T13:48:09.9187057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78439/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78439/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-07-16","Headteachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the turnover of head teachers has been in state-funded schools in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","206384"
